        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Jan. 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Huxley</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have signed the enclosed with much pleasure.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I cordially thank you for your kind, most kind, expressions about the medal.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> Sympathy &amp; not fame is the true &amp; good reward of labour.—</p>
<p>Yours most truly | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date range is conjectured by CD’s mention of the Copley Medal (see n. 3, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The enclosure has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The letter from Huxley has not been found. CD was nominated for the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4110.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Royal Society of London’s</ref> Copley Medal in 1862 and 1863 but his candidature was not successful (Royal Society, Council minutes, vol. 3 (1870), pp. 124, 160). CD was nominated again in 1864 and awarded the medal in November of that year (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 12, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4651.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Edward Sabine, 3 November 1864</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
